          "type": "text",
          "text": "What vegetables grow well in partial shade? I have a north-facing bed that only gets about four hours of sun.",
          "citations": []
        }
      ],
      "attachments": [],
      "files": [],
      "files_v2": [],
      "sync_sources": []
    },
    {
      "uuid": "b4e8d2f6-1a3c-4e5b-9d7f-8c2a6b0e4d19",
      "parent_message_uuid": "a1c3e5f7-2b4d-4a6c-8e0f-1d3b5a7c9e02",
      "sender": "assistant",
      "index": 1,
      "created_at": "2026-05-14T09:12:08.930214Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-05-14T09:13:41.201933Z",
      "truncated": false,
      "content": [
        {
          "start_timestamp": "2026-05-14T09:12:09.104562Z",
          "stop_timestamp": "2026-05-14T09:12:24.887301Z",
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Four hours of sun is enough for plenty of crops. Leafy greens and many root vegetables actually prefer some shade.\n\n| Crop | Sun needed | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Lettuce | 3–4 h | Bolts slower in shade |\n| Spinach | 3–4 h | Sow early spring |\n| Radishes | 4 h | Ready in ~30 days |\n| Chard | 4 h | Cut-and-come-again |\n\nA simple sowing plan:\n\n```text\nMarch:  spinach, radishes\nApril:  lettuce, chard\nMay:    succession-sow lettuce every 2 weeks\n```\n\nAvoid fruiting crops (tomatoes, peppers, squash) — they need 6–8 hours.",
          "citations": []
        }
      ],
